 who lived near a hazel copse."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor De Cowdray was born in 1300, in Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 3 daughters with Robert De Cowdray. She died in 1346, in her hometown, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1300–1346":"1300–1346","1295–1350":"1295–1350","1335–1378":"1335–1378","1395–1478":"1395–1478","–Female":"Surnud","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1478":"1478","1378":"1378","1300":"1300","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1295":"1295","Ormskirk, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom":"Ormskirk, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ormskirk, Lanc